<div class="blockquote">
<p>Voting doesn't help the author. Comments and critique do. I'm trying to leave critique with more of my votes, especially when they're downvotes.</p>
<div style="text-align: center;">
<p>See my reasoning here:<br />
<a href="/abolish-the-no-vote-downvote-your-friends-and-other-scp-crit">Abolish The No Vote, Downvote Your Friends, and Other Musings</a> by <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rjb-r" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1229263); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1229263&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1609973346" alt="RJB_R" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1229263)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rjb-r" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1229263); return false;">RJB_R</a></span></p>
</div>
<p>If you agree, help authors by leaving comments and critique with more of your votes.</p>
<hr />
<p>Previously, I'd vowed to leave critique with <em>every</em> downvote I made. Having spent several months doing that, I don't think it's always healthy approach. There's an ideal middle ground. Sometimes your opinions just aren't helpful, and they'll only hurt the author without helping them improve. You don't <em>always</em> have to explain yourself. Just help out when you can.</p>
<hr />
<p>You can find a bunch of reasons why I might dislike your article at the bottom of this page.</p>
<hr />
<p>If you've read an article of mine and feel like you have something to say about it, please leave a comment! Positive, negative or somewhere in between, I love knowing what my writing has made you feel/think.</p>
</div>


